BACKEND ENV — SoumyaOps
========================
Copy the lines below into a file named: backend/.env
(Node.js reads it via: import 'dotenv/config' in src/index.js)

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
PASTE THIS INTO: backend/.env
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

NODE_ENV=development
PORT=4000
API_BASE_URL=http://localhost:4000
FRONTEND_URL=http://localhost:5173

DB_HOST=localhost
DB_PORT=5432
DB_NAME=soumyaops
DB_USER=postgres
DB_PASSWORD=your_postgres_password_here

REDIS_HOST=localhost
REDIS_PORT=6379
REDIS_PASSWORD=

JWT_SECRET=replace_with_random_64_char_string_here

GITHUB_CLIENT_ID=your_github_oauth_client_id
GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET=your_github_oauth_client_secret

ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-api03-your_key_here
OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-proj-your_key_here

PINECONE_API_KEY=your_pinecone_api_key
PINECONE_INDEX_NAME=soumyaops

TELEGRAM_SECRET_TOKEN=generate_random_32_chars_here

VERCEL_TOKEN=your_vercel_token
RAILWAY_TOKEN=your_railway_token

LOG_LEVEL=info


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
WHAT EACH VARIABLE DOES — LINE BY LINE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

──────────────────────────────────────────
GROUP 1: SERVER
──────────────────────────────────────────

NODE_ENV=development
  → Tells Express which mode to run in.
  → development = detailed error messages, verbose logs
  → production  = hides internal errors from API responses for security
  → Change to "production" when you deploy to Railway.

PORT=4000
  → The port Express listens on.
  → Your frontend (Vite) proxies /api → http://localhost:4000
  → In Railway, they set PORT automatically — your code reads it with:
      const PORT = process.env.PORT || 4000;

API_BASE_URL=http://localhost:4000
  → The public URL of this backend.
  → Used ONLY for: registering Telegram webhooks.
  → Telegram needs a real HTTPS URL to send updates to.
  → In production: https://your-app.up.railway.app

FRONTEND_URL=http://localhost:5173
  → The public URL of the React frontend.
  → Used for:
      1. CORS — only this origin can call the API
      2. GitHub OAuth redirect — after login GitHub redirects back to:
         FRONTEND_URL/auth/callback?token=...
  → In production: https://your-app.vercel.app


──────────────────────────────────────────
GROUP 2: DATABASE (PostgreSQL)
──────────────────────────────────────────

DB_HOST=localhost
  → Hostname of the PostgreSQL server.
  → localhost for local dev.
  → In Railway: they give you a hostname like
    containers-us-west-1.railway.app

DB_PORT=5432
  → Standard PostgreSQL port. Almost never changes.

DB_NAME=soumyaops
  → The name of the database.
  → Created by: CREATE DATABASE soumyaops;
  → Or automatically by Docker Compose (POSTGRES_DB=soumyaops)

DB_USER=postgres
  → PostgreSQL username.

DB_PASSWORD=your_postgres_password_here
  → PostgreSQL password.
  → For local dev you set this when installing Postgres.
  → For Railway/Neon/Supabase they give you a connection string —
    you can parse it or use the individual variables.

  HOW CONNECTION POOL WORKS:
  src/config/database.js creates a Pool with max 20 connections.
  Every query goes through: query(sql, params) → pool.query()
  Pool reuses connections automatically. No need to open/close manually.


──────────────────────────────────────────
GROUP 3: REDIS
──────────────────────────────────────────

REDIS_HOST=localhost
REDIS_PORT=6379
REDIS_PASSWORD=
  → Redis is used for TWO things:
      1. BullMQ job queues (embed, deploy, analyze, fix, log-process)
      2. Session caching (future use)
  → Leave REDIS_PASSWORD empty for local Redis with no auth.
  → For production use Upstash (free tier works) or Railway Redis.
  → IMPORTANT: BullMQ requires maxRetriesPerRequest: null in the
    Redis connection config — already set in src/config/redis.js


──────────────────────────────────────────
GROUP 4: AUTH
──────────────────────────────────────────

JWT_SECRET=replace_with_random_64_char_string_here
  → Used to sign and verify JWT tokens (user sessions).
  → Generate it with this command:
      node -e "console.log(require('crypto').randomBytes(64).toString('hex'))"
  → Must be at least 32 characters. 64 is better.
  → If you change this, ALL existing tokens become invalid (all users logged out).
  → NEVER commit this to git. Keep it secret.

  HOW JWTs WORK IN THIS APP:
  Login → backend creates JWT with { userId, username }
  Frontend stores it in localStorage (via Zustand persist)
  Every API call sends: Authorization: Bearer <token>
  auth.middleware.js verifies it with jwt.verify(token, JWT_SECRET)
  If valid → req.user = { id, username }  → controller runs
  If invalid → 401 response → frontend auto-logs-out


──────────────────────────────────────────
GROUP 5: GITHUB OAUTH
──────────────────────────────────────────

GITHUB_CLIENT_ID=your_github_oauth_client_id
GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET=your_github_oauth_client_secret

  HOW TO CREATE:
  1. Go to: github.com → Settings → Developer settings → OAuth Apps
  2. Click "New OAuth App"
  3. Fill in:
       Application name: SoumyaOps
       Homepage URL:     http://localhost:5173
       Callback URL:     http://localhost:4000/api/auth/github/callback
  4. Click "Register application"
  5. Copy Client ID → GITHUB_CLIENT_ID
  6. Click "Generate a new client secret" → GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET

  HOW LOGIN FLOW WORKS:
  User clicks Login
  → GET /api/auth/github
  → Redirect to github.com/login/oauth/authorize?client_id=...
  → User approves on GitHub
  → GitHub redirects to /api/auth/github/callback?code=abc123
  → Backend exchanges code for access_token
  → Backend fetches github.com/api/user (profile)
  → Backend upserts user in PostgreSQL
  → Backend creates JWT
  → Redirect to FRONTEND_URL/auth/callback?token=<jwt>
  → Frontend stores token in localStorage


──────────────────────────────────────────
GROUP 6: AI / RAG
──────────────────────────────────────────

ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-api03-your_key_here
  → Get from: console.anthropic.com → API Keys
  → Used for:
      1. RAG answer generation (rag.service.js)
         Model: claude-sonnet-4-20250514
      2. Fix generation (fix-generator.service.js)
         Same model, asked to return JSON
  → Costs: billed per token. Each RAG query uses ~2000-4000 tokens.

OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-proj-your_key_here
  → Get from: platform.openai.com/api-keys
  → Used for:
      1. Embeddings: text-embedding-3-large (3072 dimensions)
         Every message/document/code chunk gets embedded.
         Costs: ~$0.00013 per 1000 tokens (very cheap)
      2. Whisper: whisper-1 model
         Converts Telegram voice notes to text.
         Costs: $0.006 per minute of audio

  WHY OPENAI FOR EMBEDDINGS, NOT ANTHROPIC?
  Anthropic does not offer a public embedding API.
  OpenAI's text-embedding-3-large is currently the best embedding
  model available, producing 3072-dimensional vectors with high
  semantic accuracy for code and natural language.


──────────────────────────────────────────
GROUP 7: PINECONE (Vector Database)
──────────────────────────────────────────

PINECONE_API_KEY=your_pinecone_api_key
PINECONE_INDEX_NAME=soumyaops

  HOW TO SET UP PINECONE:
  1. Create free account at pinecone.io
  2. Click "Create Index"
  3. Settings:
       Name:       soumyaops
       Dimensions: 3072   ← MUST match text-embedding-3-large output
       Metric:     cosine ← measures similarity between vectors
       Type:       Serverless (easiest) or Pod
  4. Copy API key from the console → PINECONE_API_KEY

  HOW NAMESPACES WORK:
  Each workspace gets its own namespace inside the single index:
    Workspace "team-alpha" → namespace "ws-team-alpha-1a2b3c"
    Workspace "team-beta"  → namespace "ws-team-beta-4d5e6f"
  This means workspace A can NEVER see workspace B's vectors.
  All isolation happens at the Pinecone namespace level.

  WHAT GETS STORED:
  Every chunk from every source (Telegram, code, logs, documents)
  gets converted to a 3072-dimensional vector and stored here.
  Metadata stored alongside: source, workspaceId, fileName, timestamp, text


──────────────────────────────────────────
GROUP 8: TELEGRAM
──────────────────────────────────────────

TELEGRAM_SECRET_TOKEN=generate_random_32_chars_here
  → Generate with:
      node -e "console.log(require('crypto').randomBytes(32).toString('hex'))"
  → You configure this when setting the webhook on Telegram:
      POST https://api.telegram.org/bot<token>/setWebhook
      { "url": "...", "secret_token": "YOUR_SECRET" }
  → Telegram then sends X-Telegram-Bot-Api-Secret-Token header
    on every webhook request.
  → Your backend checks this header to reject fake requests.
  → setBotWebhook() in telegram.ingest.js handles this automatically.

  WHY WEBHOOK NOT POLLING?
  Polling: your server asks Telegram "any new messages?" every second.
    → Slow (1 second delay minimum)
    → Wastes resources
  Webhook: Telegram pushes updates to your server instantly.
    → Zero delay
    → Efficient
    → Requires a public HTTPS URL (so localhost doesn't work directly)
    → Use ngrok for local testing: ngrok http 4000


──────────────────────────────────────────
GROUP 9: DEPLOYMENT PLATFORMS
──────────────────────────────────────────

VERCEL_TOKEN=your_vercel_token
  → Get from: vercel.com → Account Settings → Tokens
  → Click "Create Token" → choose "Full Account" scope
  → Used to:
      Create Vercel projects programmatically
      Inject environment variables
      Trigger deployments
  → Frontend apps (React, Next.js, Vue) go here.

RAILWAY_TOKEN=your_railway_token
  → Get from: railway.app → Account Settings → Tokens
  → Click "New Token"
  → Used to call Railway's GraphQL API:
      Create projects
      Create services from GitHub repos
      Set environment variables
      Trigger deployments
  → Backend apps (Node.js, Python, Go) go here.


──────────────────────────────────────────
GROUP 10: LOGGING
──────────────────────────────────────────

LOG_LEVEL=info
  → Controls how much is logged to console and log files.
  → debug  = everything including SQL queries, job events, all HTTP requests
  → info   = normal operations (server start, job complete, DB connect)
  → warn   = non-critical issues (retry attempts, missing optional data)
  → error  = only failures and exceptions
  → Use "debug" when debugging, "info" in production.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
MINIMUM REQUIRED TO START LOCALLY
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

You MUST fill in these before npm run dev works:

1. DB_PASSWORD           → your local Postgres password
2. JWT_SECRET            → generate random 64 chars
3. GITHUB_CLIENT_ID      → from OAuth App you create
4. GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET  → from OAuth App you create
5. ANTHROPIC_API_KEY     → from console.anthropic.com
6. OPENAI_API_KEY        → from platform.openai.com
7. PINECONE_API_KEY      → from pinecone.io (create index first)

These are OPTIONAL for basic local testing:
  TELEGRAM_SECRET_TOKEN  → only needed to connect a Telegram bot
  VERCEL_TOKEN           → only needed to deploy via SoumyaOps
  RAILWAY_TOKEN          → only needed to deploy via SoumyaOps


